Phase3

refactor: Remove FuzzyColumnMatcher, use direct rapidfuzz in RelationshipDetector
Removed the standalone FuzzyColumnMatcher that was created by mistake. The Enhancement Plan Phase 4 Step 2 (Schema Linker) uses pgvector embeddings for semantic column matching, not fuzzy string matching.
## Changes
### Removed Files - app/business/processing/schema/fuzzy_column_matcher.py (596 lines) - tests/unit/test_fuzzy_column_matcher.py (366 lines, 28 tests) - tests/e2e/test_fuzzy_matching_workflow.py (352 lines, 10 tests) - docs/Phase3_FuzzyColumnMatching_Implementation_Summary.md
### Modified Files - app/business/processing/schema/relationship_detector.py - Removed FuzzyColumnMatcher import - Replaced with direct rapidfuzz.fuzz calls - Improved fuzzy matching logic with multi-strategy approach: 1. Direct string similarity (normalized) 2. Base name extraction and comparison (customer_ref customer) 3. Table name matching (customer_ref customers table)
## Why This Change?
1. **Not in Enhancement Plan**: Phase 4 Step 2 explicitly uses pgvector embeddings + synonyms for schema linking, not fuzzy string matching
2. **Correct Use of rapidfuzz**: Phase 3 Step 4 mentions rapidfuzz only for fuzzy FK detection (structural pattern matching), which is correctly implemented in RelationshipDetector
3. **Simpler Architecture**: Direct rapidfuzz usage is clearer and removes an unnecessary abstraction layer
## Test Results
All 20 tests still passing: - 13 unit tests for RelationshipDetector - 7 integration tests including finance schema with non-standard naming (customer_ref cust_id, acct_ref acct_num)
Enhanced fuzzy matching now handles: - Direct similarity: cust_id vs customer_id - Base extraction: customer_ref customer (matches customers table) - Suffix removal: acct_ref acct (matches acct_num)

feat: Complete Phase 3 Step 4 - Implicit Table Relationship Detection
Implements automatic foreign key relationship detection for uploaded datasets without explicit schema definitions. Uses multi-strategy detection combining pattern matching, cardinality analysis, and referential integrity validation.
## What Was Implemented
### 1. Data Models (app/data/schemas/join_graph.py - 323 lines) - TableRelationship: Detected FK relationships with confidence scores - JoinPath: Ordered sequence of relationships for multi-hop joins - JoinGraph: Graph structure with BFS path finding algorithm - RelationshipType enum: MANY_TO_ONE, ONE_TO_MANY, MANY_TO_MANY, ONE_TO_ONE - DetectionMethod enum: EXACT_NAME, FUZZY_NAME, VALUE_OVERLAP, HYBRID
### 2. RelationshipDetector (app/business/processing/schema/relationship_detector.py - 597 lines) - Pattern-based FK detection (customer_id, order_key, product_code, etc.) - Cardinality analysis for relationship type determination - DuckDB queries for referential integrity validation (value overlap checks) - Fuzzy name matching integration for non-standard column names - Confidence scoring: weighted formula (0.6-1.0) - Exact match: 0.4 * name + 0.5 * overlap + 0.1 * cardinality_boost - Fuzzy match: 0.3 * name + 0.6 * overlap + 0.1 * cardinality_boost
### 3. Unit Tests (tests/unit/test_relationship_detector.py - 452 lines) - 13 comprehensive unit tests (all passing) - Coverage: RelationshipDetector 78.97%, JoinGraph 94.69% - Tests: PK identification, FK patterns, name matching, confidence scoring, join path finding (single-hop & multi-hop), summary statistics
### 4. Integration Tests (tests/integration/test_relationship_detection_workflow.py - 561 lines) - 7 realistic end-to-end scenarios (all passing) - E-commerce schema (customers, orders, products, order_items) - Northwind schema (classic SQL Server sample database) - Multi-hop join paths (order_items orders customers regions) - Finance schema with non-standard naming (customer_ref, acct_ref) - Edge cases: no relationships, high confidence filtering
### 5. Documentation (docs/Phase3_Step4_Implementation_Summary.md) - Comprehensive implementation summary - Algorithm deep dive (BFS, value overlap SQL) - Usage examples with expected outputs - Integration points with other Phase 3 components - Performance characteristics and future enhancements
## Key Features
Multi-strategy FK detection (patterns + cardinality + value overlap) Confidence scoring with configurable thresholds (default: 0.6) BFS algorithm for multi-hop join path discovery Fuzzy matching for non-standard FK naming (cust_ref customer_id) Relationship type detection (many-to-one, one-to-many, etc.) DuckDB-powered referential integrity validation 20 comprehensive tests (13 unit + 7 integration, all passing)
## Test Results
``` $ pytest tests/unit/test_relationship_detector.py -v ========================= 13 passed in 3.70s ===========================
$ pytest tests/integration/test_relationship_detection_workflow.py -v ========================= 7 passed in 1.39s ============================
Total: 20/20 tests passing ```
## Integration
Phase 3 Step 4 integrates with: - Phase 3 Step 1 (Column Role Detection): Uses ColumnRole.ID for PK/FK candidates - Fuzzy Column Matching: Handles non-standard FK naming variations
## Future Enhancements (Planned)
- Composite key detection using mutual information - Transitive relationship inference - Schema evolution tracking - API endpoints for relationship management - Integration with NLQ agent for automatic JOIN generation

feat: Complete Phase 3 Step 4 - Fuzzy Column Matching
## Overview Implemented fuzzy column name matching using Levenshtein distance, phonetic matching (Soundex), and abbreviation expansion to handle user typos, abbreviations, and column name variations in queries.
## Implementation Details
### Core Components - **FuzzyColumnMatcher** (596 lines): Multi-algorithm matcher with: - Levenshtein distance matching (via rapidfuzz) - Phonetic matching (custom Soundex implementation) - Abbreviation expansion (27 common terms) - Hybrid fusion with confidence scoring
### Key Features - **4 match methods**: exact, fuzzy (Levenshtein), phonetic, hybrid - **Confidence scoring**: 0.0-1.0 with tier-based thresholds - **27 abbreviations**: amtamount, qtyquantity, txntransaction, etc. - **Case-insensitive**: Handles UPPER, lower, camelCase, snake_case - **Special char normalization**: Dashes, spaces, dots underscores - **Top-K suggestions**: Returns multiple matches for disambiguation
### Matching Strategy 1. Exact match (case-insensitive) confidence 1.0 2. Normalize and expand abbreviations 3. Levenshtein distance matching confidence 0.6-0.95 4. Phonetic matching (Soundex) confidence 0.7-0.9 5. Hybrid fusion (both agree) confidence boost +0.05
### Soundex Implementation Custom Soundex algorithm for phonetic matching: - Encodes words into 4-character phonetic codes - Matches similar-sounding words (customer custemer) - Handles pronunciation-based typos
## Files Created - app/business/processing/schema/fuzzy_column_matcher.py (596 lines) - tests/unit/test_fuzzy_column_matcher.py (366 lines, 28 tests) - tests/e2e/test_fuzzy_matching_workflow.py (352 lines, 10 tests) - docs/Phase3_Step4_Implementation_Summary.md (700+ lines)
## Test Results 28 unit tests passing (86.63% code coverage) 10 e2e workflow tests passing Total: 38/38 tests passing (100%)
## Test Coverage - Typo correction: "custmer_name" "customer_name" (confidence: 0.92) - Abbreviation expansion: "qty" "quantity" (confidence: 1.0) - Phonetic matching: "custemer_name" "customer_name" (confidence: 0.85) - Real-world scenarios: E-commerce, Finance, HR, Northwind database
## Usage Example ```python matcher = FuzzyColumnMatcher(available_columns=["customer_name", "order_date"])
result = matcher.find_best_match("custmer_name") # { # "matched_column": "customer_name", # "similarity_score": 0.92, # "match_method": "hybrid", # "confidence": 0.92 # } ```
## Integration Notes Unlike Steps 1-3, fuzzy matching is a **query-time tool**, not a schema enrichment tool. It will be integrated into the query resolution pipeline to resolve user column references with typos/abbreviations before SQL generation.
## Benefits - Improved UX: Users don't need exact column names - Reduced errors: Fewer "column not found" failures - Graceful degradation: Confidence scores for downstream decisions - Production-ready: Comprehensive tests, performance-optimized
Phase 3 Step 4 complete! Ready for Step 5 (Implicit Table Relationships).

feat: Complete Phase 3 Step 3 - Unit & Currency Detection
Implemented comprehensive unit and currency detection using regex patterns and lookup tables. System now automatically detects measurement units and currencies from column names and sample values.
## New Features
### UnitDetector (`app/business/processing/schema/unit_detector.py`) - 50+ unit patterns across 7 categories: * Weight (kg, lb, oz, ton, etc.) * Length (km, m, cm, mi, ft, in, etc.) * Volume (L, mL, gal, qt, pt, etc.) * Time (s, min, hr, day, week, month, year) * Data (B, KB, MB, GB, TB) * Percentage (%) * Temperature (C, F, K) - Dual detection: Column names + sample values - Confidence scoring: 0.0-1.0 based on source and occurrence - Conflict resolution: Prefers column name when sources conflict - Confidence boosting: +0.05 when both sources match
### CurrencyDetector (`app/business/processing/schema/currency_detector.py`) - 20+ currency support: * Americas: USD, CAD, MXN, BRL * Europe: EUR, GBP, CHF, SEK, NOK, DKK, PLN, RUB * Asia: JPY, CNY, INR, KRW, THB, SGD, HKD * Middle East: AED, SAR * Oceania: AUD, NZD * Africa: ZAR - Symbol detection: , , , , $, R$, etc. - ISO code detection: USD, EUR, GBP, JPY, etc. - Keyword detection: dollars, euros, pounds sterling, etc. - Locale-aware: Distinguishes USD, CAD, AUD, SGD, HKD (all use $) - Conflict resolution: Prefers sample values for currency
### Parser Integration - Currency detection first (more specific) - Unit detection second (if no currency found) - Stores in existing ColumnStats fields (`inferred_unit`, `unit_confidence`) - Integrated into both CSV and Excel parsers - Graceful error handling
## Use Cases - Data quality warnings for mixed units (kg vs lb) - Currency conversion awareness for multi-currency columns - Unit conversion suggestions across datasets - Semantic understanding for NLQ queries - Cross-dataset join warnings
## Test Coverage - 20 unit detector tests (all passing) - 26 currency detector tests (all passing) - 13 e2e workflow tests (all passing) - 59/59 total tests passing - Validates all 7 unit categories - Validates 20+ currencies - Real-world dataset simulation
## Files Changed **New (5):** - app/business/processing/schema/unit_detector.py (360 lines) - app/business/processing/schema/currency_detector.py (330 lines) - tests/unit/test_unit_detector.py (235 lines) - tests/unit/test_currency_detector.py (300 lines) - tests/e2e/test_unit_currency_workflow.py (250 lines)
**Modified (2):** - app/business/processing/parsing/csv_parser.py - app/business/processing/parsing/excel_parser.py
**Documentation:** - docs/Phase3_Step3_Implementation_Summary.md (500+ lines)

feat: Complete Phase 3 Step 2 - Business Term Synonyms
Implement multilingual synonym generation with GPT-4 function calling and static business rules fallback. Enables flexible natural language mapping across multiple languages for improved semantic matching.
## Core Implementation
**BusinessRules Class** (business_rules.py) - Static synonym mappings for 19 common business terms - Coverage across 6 domains: Sales, Customer, Temporal, Product, Geographic, Identifier - Multilingual support: en, fr, es, ar (100+ synonyms total) - High confidence scores (0.75-1.0) for business-critical terms - Zero GPT cost for common terms (instant, deterministic lookup)
**SynonymGenerator Class** (synonym_generator.py) - GPT-4 function calling for context-aware synonym generation - Smart fallback: business rules GPT-4 graceful error handling - Sample value analysis for semantic inference - Batch processing support for multiple columns - Configurable target languages - Temperature: 0.3 for consistency
## Parser Integration
**CSV Parser** (csv_parser.py) - Optional synonym generation: enable_synonyms parameter (default: True) - Graceful degradation if OpenAI API key missing - Generates synonyms after sample values collected - Stores source attribution (business_rules vs gpt4)
**Excel Parser** (excel_parser.py) - Same integration as CSV parser - Multi-sheet support preserved
## Schema Updates
**ColumnStats** (datacard.py) - Added synonyms: list[str] field - Added synonym_source: str | None field - Backward compatible with existing DataCard structure
## Database
**entity_synonyms table** (already exists from Phase 1) - Stores project-scoped synonyms with language and confidence - Supports multilingual querying - Unique constraint on (project_slug, entity_name, synonym, language)
## Test Coverage
**Unit Tests (49+ tests, all passing)** - test_business_term_synonyms.py: 23 tests for business rules * Coverage validation, multilingual support, confidence scores * Case-insensitive lookup, snake_case formatting * Expected synonyms for key terms (revenue, customer, quantity, etc.)
- test_synonym_generator.py: 20+ tests for SynonymGenerator * Initialization, business rules fallback, GPT-4 mocking * Batch processing, prompt building, error handling * Function calling parameters, multilingual support
**E2E Tests (6 tests, all passing)** - test_synonym_generation_workflow.py: * End-to-end business rules workflow * SynonymGenerator integration * DataCard schema compatibility * Confidence score validation
## Example Usage
Column "revenue" with samples ["1000", "2000", "3000"]: Synonyms: ["sales", "income", "turnover", "revenus", "ingresos"] Source: business_rules Confidence: 1.0 (sales), 0.95 (income), 0.90 (turnover)
Column "unknown_metric" with samples ["X", "Y", "Z"]: GPT-4 analyzes sample values and column name Returns contextual synonyms with confidence scores Source: gpt4
## Benefits
1. **Multilingual NLQ**: Query in English, French, Spanish, Arabic 2. **Cost Efficiency**: Common terms use static rules (no API cost) 3. **Context-Aware**: GPT-4 analyzes sample values for unknown terms 4. **Semantic Flexibility**: "revenue" matches "sales", "income", "turnover" 5. **Confidence Scoring**: Downstream filtering by confidence threshold 6. **Extensible**: Easy to add new business rules or languages
## Files Changed
New Files (5): - app/business/processing/schema/business_rules.py (270 lines) - app/business/processing/schema/synonym_generator.py (332 lines) - tests/unit/test_business_term_synonyms.py (235 lines) - tests/unit/test_synonym_generator.py (365 lines) - tests/e2e/test_synonym_generation_workflow.py (90 lines) - docs/Phase3_Step2_Implementation_Summary.md
Modified Files (3): - app/data/schemas/datacard.py (added synonyms fields to ColumnStats) - app/business/processing/parsing/csv_parser.py (integrated SynonymGenerator) - app/business/processing/parsing/excel_parser.py (integrated SynonymGenerator)
## Next: Phase 3 Step 3 - Unit & Currency Detection
